node.text: Join spacesuit engineer Lindsay Aitchison and singer Gregory Porter for a talk on next-generation spacesuits! Lindsay helped designed our new, Artemis generation spacesuits that will be worn on future missions to the Moon. The duo discuss the spacesuit worn in Gregory's latest music video, spacesuits for the Moon and our Perseverance rover's upcoming mission to Mars. 🚀

🎧 Our headquarters building in Washington, D.C., will soon be named after Mary W. Jackson, the first African-American female engineer at @NASA. Jackson started her NASA career in the West Area Computing Unit of the agency’s Langley Research Center in Hampton, Virginia. Jackson, a mathematician and aerospace engineer, went on to lead programs influencing the hiring and promotion of women in NASA's science, technology, engineering, and mathematics careers. In 2019, she was posthumously awarded the Congressional Gold Medal.

node.text:
By combining Lunar Reconnaissance Orbiter data with supercomputer modeling, scientists have created these high-resolution elevation maps of four potential #Artemis mission landing sites near the Moon’s South Pole. The color scale is in kilometers (km), and the pixel scale is 5 meters per pixel.

The South Pole presents both promise and challenge, most notably due to the region’s extreme lighting and temperature conditions. Permanently shadowed regions inside craters have temperatures reaching below -173°C (-280°F), making them “cold traps” for volatiles including water in the form of ice. Favorable illumination conditions are also important to ensure that there is enough sunlight available to power landed assets and infrastructure. Well-lit, tall peaks provide the right illumination conditions and some of the South Pole’s permanently shadowed regions lie near such peaks.

Figure credit: Michael Barker, @nasagoddard

node.text:
#TBT Pictured here, the launch platform and vehicle for space shuttle mission STS-36 were rolled out to Launch Pad 39A at @nasakennedy on January 25, 1990. The distance between the Vehicle Assembly Building (VAB) and Pad 39A is about 3.4 miles (approximately 5.4 kilometers). 

Before the Space Launch System (SLS) can lift off for the #Artemis I mission, the rocket will first make the 4.2-mile trek (about 6.7 km) from the VAB to Launch Pad 39B along the path called the crawlerway.

For Artemis I, the crawlerway must be able to support 25.5 million pounds (~11.5 million kg) to withstand the massive weight of the Crawler Transporter-2, the SLS rocket, the Orion capsule, and the mobile launcher.

“Our Artemis team is not about a single team member, but rather, the work of everyone as we bring our best to launch this rocket on a mission of a lifetime.” - Charlie Blackwell-Thompson

Over the last few years, under the leadership of Artemis I Launch Director Charlie Blackwell-Thompson, teams with @nasa’s Exploration Ground Systems and contractor companies at @nasakennedy have worked through multiple launch simulations, and now, those teams are kicking it up a notch.

Six more joint launch simulations are scheduled to take place before the Space Launch System and Orion blast off from Kennedy’s Launch Pad 39B – three that will focus on cryogenic loading and three focusing on the terminal countdown. All of these will help certify that the #Artemis I launch team is ready to handle anything thrown their way on launch day.

Image Credits: NASA/Ben Smegelsky

node.text:
A molten Moon 🌋

Shortly after it formed, the Moon was covered in a global ocean of molten rock or magma. As the magma ocean cooled and solidified, dense minerals sank to form the mantle layer, while less-dense minerals floated to form the surface crust. Later intense bombardment by massive asteroids and comets punched through the crust, blasting out pieces of mantle and scattering them across the lunar surface.

Recently, a pair of NASA studies identified the most likely locations to find pieces of mantle on the surface, providing a map for future lunar sample return missions such as those under #Artemis. If collected and analyzed, these fragments from deep within the Moon can provide a better understanding of how the Moon, the Earth, and many other solar system worlds evolved.

Credits: @NASA/LRO/Lunar Prospector/D. Moriarty

They see me rollin’ 😎

#OTD 50 years ago Apollo 15 Commander David Scott became the first human to drive on another planetary body when he drove the lunar roving vehicle on the surface of the Moon.

Apollo 15 launched on July 26, 1971, and landed on the lunar surface on July 30. During the mission, Scott and lunar module pilot James Irwin collected 170 pounds (~77 kilograms) of lunar material during their more than 18 hours on the Moon's surface.
